    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Hairy Cell Leukemia", content: "Hairy cell leukemia (HCL) is a rare, indolent B-cell lymphoproliferative disorder characterized by accumulation of mature B lymphocytes with fine cytoplasmic projections (giving the 'hairy' appearance on peripheral blood smear) in the bone marrow, spleen, and peripheral blood. The malignant cells harbor the BRAF V600E mutation in virtually all cases, leading to constitutive activation of the MAPK signaling pathway that promotes cell survival and proliferation. HCL cells infiltrate the bone marrow diffusely, causing myelofibrosis and pancytopenia (anemia, neutropenia, thrombocytopenia), and massively infiltrate the spleen, causing marked splenomegaly. The pancytopenia is disproportionate to marrow infiltration because HCL cells secrete cytokines that suppress normal hematopoiesis. The RN monitors CBC for cytopenias, assesses for signs of infection (neutropenia is the primary cause of morbidity), implements neutropenic precautions, assesses spleen size (risk of splenic rupture), administers cladribine or pentostatin chemotherapy as prescribed, monitors for tumor lysis syndrome during treatment, and educates patients about the excellent prognosis with greater than 90% complete remission rates with purine analog therapy." },
